{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652018"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:32:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18507"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18507"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.08,0.54,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11236"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11236"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6958"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26911"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver receives a dual blood supply and has a unique venous drainage system that is essential for its function in processing nutrients from the digestive tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its venous drainage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatic veins drain into the portal vein","Hepatic veins drain into the azygos vein","Hepatic veins drain into the inferior vena cava","Portal vein drains into the superior vena cava","Portal vein drains directly into the right atrium"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatic veins drain into the inferior vena cava (image)\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The hepatic veins collect deoxygenated blood from the liver and empty directly into the inferior vena cava just below the diaphragm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic veins drain into the portal vein\u003C/strong\u003E - This would create a closed loop and prevent blood from returning to the heart\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic veins drain into the azygos vein\u003C/strong\u003E - The hepatic veins drain directly into the inferior vena cava, not the azygos system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal vein drains into the superior vena cava\u003C/strong\u003E - The portal vein delivers blood to the liver, not to the superior vena cava\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal vein drains directly into the right atrium\u003C/strong\u003E - The portal vein delivers blood to the liver sinusoids, not the heart\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe portal vein forms behind the neck of the pancreas from the union of the superior mesenteric and splenic veins. It carries nutrient-rich blood from the gastrointestinal tract to the liver for processing before the blood returns to the heart via the hepatic veins and inferior vena cava.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The portal vein is formed by the union of the superior mesenteric and splenic veins behind the neck of the pancreas.","The portal vein carries nutrient-rich blood from the gastrointestinal tract and spleen to the liver.","The hepatic veins drain deoxygenated blood from the liver directly into the inferior vena cava."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cLiver veins\u201d by Marcelo Reis\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Liver_veins.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18507"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21408"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21408"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2reWeuHQOW5myFOZZlQUINML18VBR5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2reWeuHQOW5myFOZZlQUINML18VBR5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":434}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T12:20:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T12:21:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11236"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":n